@flexiarg math-strategy/structural-relation-result
@title Structural-Relation-Result Family
@sigils [⇌/連]
@keywords relation, equivalence, inclusion, transfer, generalization, bridge, family-parent
@audience mathematicians, paper-writers, pattern-classifiers
@tone classification / heuristic
@factor Wisdom (paññā)
@references [math-informal/transport-across-isomorphism math-informal/find-the-right-abstraction math-informal/reduce-to-known-result math-strategy/convention-bridge]

! conclusion:
  Your paper relates two structures — by equivalence, by inclusion, by
  theorem-transfer to a new class, or by extending a theory's scope.

  + context: Two structures (or one structure and a theory) are in view; the
    question is how they correspond. The paper does not (primarily) describe a
    single structure or assert existence; it builds a bridge.

  + IF:
      The paper's main contribution can be expressed as "X and Y are equivalent",
      or "X is contained in Y" (with a directional structural argument), or
      "the theorem T holds for the new class C", or "we extend theory T to a
      broader setting".

  + HOWEVER:
      Structural-relation papers are the second-most-populous family in our
      pilot (≈ 25 % — see `futon3/holes/excursions/E-math-prototype-pilot.md`
      Phase 2). The leaves diverge: equivalence is symmetric, inclusion is
      directional, transfer is "we re-prove T in setting C", generalization is
      "we extend T's framework to admit new objects". They share a *bridge-
      building* shape but the proof obligations differ.

  + THEN:
      1. Decide whether the relation is symmetric (equivalence), directional
         (inclusion / monotonicity), a theorem-transfer (re-proving in a new
         class), or a theory-extension (generalising the framework).
      2. Pick the matching leaf member-pattern.
      3. Identify the *witness* of the relation: a map, an embedding, a
         re-proof, a strict containment of a parameter family.

  + BECAUSE:
      Bridge-building is structurally different from describing or asserting
      existence. The "tension" being relieved is the *gap between two formerly
      separate structures*; the "move" is a constructed correspondence; the
      "witness" is the correspondence itself plus its preserved-property
      checks. Per the BHK framing of M-pattern-application-diagnostic, this
      family includes the most structurally rich BHK arrows in the corpus.

  + MEMBER-PATTERNS:
      member[math-informal/transport-across-isomorphism]      # equivalence / transfer
      member[math-informal/find-the-right-abstraction]        # generalization
      member[math-informal/reduce-to-known-result]            # cross-domain bridge
      member[math-informal/structural-inclusion]              # inclusion / monotonicity (new leaf)

  + EXEMPLAR-PAPERS:
      exemplar[arxiv-2604.20808v1]   # Coxeter cohomology equivalence
      exemplar[arxiv-2604.20785v1]   # Thurston norm inclusion
      exemplar[arxiv-2604.20818v1]   # Coburn → edge-modes bridge
      exemplar[arxiv-2604.20778v1]   # Infinite matroid generalization
      exemplar[arxiv-math/0603598v1] # Noether to fractional control

  + NEXT-STEPS:
      next[Decide whether the relation is equivalence, inclusion, transfer, or generalization.]
      next[Identify the bridge object: map, embedding, re-proof, or framework extension.]
      next[Cross-check: does the relation *preserve* the properties of interest, or only *correspond on a subset*?]
